Peer Health Shocks and Labor Supply

Evidence from Professional Athletes

Joshua C. Martin
joshua.martin@vanderbilt.edu

Vanderbilt University

October 21, 2024

Introduction

Motivation

  • Understanding factors that shape perceptions of risk and uncertainty has long been a central focus of social science, influencing decisions ranging from savings, investment, insurance, market behavior and price formation while informing theory and policy.
  • Research often examines how education, culture, and social networks shape preferences and how these channels reduce informational gaps.

Introduction

Overview

  • I examine the degree to which peers influence risk perceptions, focusing on labor supply decisions of athletes whose teammates died from work-related injuries.

  • This setting:

    • Identifies peers across time and space,
    • Limits concerns about endogenous peer selection,
    • Allows for the construction of characteristically similar counterfactual groups,
    • Offers insight into wage determination in a relatively free market.

Introduction

Findings

  • Athletes with a former teammate who died of CTE are 2.2-4.0 percentage points (8-23%) more likely to retire.
    • Mechanisms: familiarity, recency, opportunity costs, wage flexibility
    • Placebo: no effect for non-safety-related deaths
    • Treated athletes exhibit higher risk sensitivity, opting for larger signing bonuses and shorter contracts at lower salaries.
  • âTreatedâ workers value this health shock disamenity at $6M and need a $1M raise to remain indifferent to exiting.

Introduction

Contribution

  • Peers influence risk perceptions across various domains:
    • Retirement savings (Duflo and Saez 2003)
    • Mortgages and home insurance (Bailey et al. 2018; Hu 2022)
    • Health insurance purchases (Innocenti et al. 2019)
    • Technology adoption (Oster and Thornton 2012)
    • Seat belt use (Robertson, OâNeill, and Wixom 1972)
  • I show that risk perception is highly sensitive to peer outcomes, even where this information is conveyed indirectly and where these risks are highly-publicized.

Overview of Literature

  • Peer effects are frequently studied in randomized settings, such as classrooms and workplaces, with research showing impacts on income, education, health behaviors, social attitudes and productivity (Chetty et al. 2011; Sacerdote 2001; Kremer and Levy 2008; Carrell, Hoekstra, and West 2019; Falk and Ichino 2006; Mas and Moretti 2009; Cohen-Zada, Dayag, and Gershoni 2024).
  • In non-competitive labor markets, injury risks may not be fully reflected in wages (Fishback and Kantor 1992; Bender and Mridha 2011; Lavetti 2020).
  • In sports, wages have been show to be responsive to employer characteristics and location amenities, injury risk and the risk or re-injury (Michaelides 2010; Dole and Kassis 2010; Anderson 2022)

Setting

CTE

  • CTE is an irreversible neurodegenerative condition that arises from repeated head impacts over extended periods.
    • Symptoms: motor impairments, difficulties regulating emotion, nerve pain, and dementia, often presenting as having advanced Parkinsonâs and Alzheimerâs disease.
    • Treatment: symptom management
    • Age profile: 20s - 80s
    • Diagnosis: post-mortem; analysis of brain tissue

Setting

CTE

  • CTE has become synonymous with violent collision sports, especially American football.
    • Two published academic papers identified the condition in former NFL players (Bennet I. Omalu et al. 2005; Bennet I. Omalu et al. 2006).
  • Before the term âCTE,â post-concussive symptoms in athletes were referred to as having oneâs âbell rung,â being âpunch drunk,â or âshell shocked.â
    • These terms implied rare, worst-case outcomes experienced by reckless individuals, with transitory effects.

Setting

CTE

  • All athletes diagnosed with CTE from 2005-2008 shared numerous common traits: long professional careers, disproportionate exposure to repeated head trauma, and violent styles of play.

  • This changed in 2009 with the discovery of CTE in Chris Henry.

    • The collision-averse Henry had played competitive football for fewer than ten years before he died at age 26.

  • In 14 months in 2010-2011, 4 hockey players (3 of whom were still active professionals) died and were diagnosed with CTE at the ages of 45, 35, 28, and 27. Google Trends Timeline

Theoretical Framework

Wokrersâ Maximize Utility

\[U_i = \sum_{t=T_0}^{T} \delta^{t-T_0} \left( d_{ist} \cdot \omega_{ist} + (1 - d_{ist}) \cdot \eta_{ist} \right)\]

  • \(U_i\) = utility of individual \(i\) over the periods from \(t\) to \(T\)

  • \(\delta\) = discount factor; reflects time preferences; \(0 < \delta < 1\),

  • \(d_{ist} \in \{0, 1\}\); whether employed in sports

  • \(\omega_{ist}\) = sport wage

  • \(\eta_{ist}\) = non-sport wage

Theoretical Framework

Non-Sport Wages

\[\eta_{ist} = \mu_i - \theta_{ist}\]

  • \(\mu\): workerâs human capital value

  • \(\theta\): reduction in working years due to physical toll from violent sports

\[\theta_{ist} = \gamma_{st} + \epsilon_{ist}\] - \(\gamma\) = known (âinherentâ) dangers of the sport

  • Full-information of workplace safety \(\implies E[\epsilon] = 0\)

Theoretical Framework

Sport Wages

\[\omega_{ist} = \rho_{st} \cdot \upsilon_{ist} + \beta_{ist} \cdot \theta_{ist}\]

  • \(\rho\) = market demand

  • \(\upsilon\) = value of the marginal product of labor (relative to replacement worker)

  • \(\beta\) = workersâ bargaining power

\[\beta_{ist} = \mu_i + \pi_{st} \cdot \upsilon_{ist}\] - \(\pi\) = strength of collective bargaining agreement

Theoretical Framework

Predictions: Full Information

  • Workers will remain working in sports if \(\omega_{ist} \geq \eta_{ist}\)

  • Changes in the decision to remain in sports:

\[ \Delta_{it} (\rho_{ist} + \epsilon_{ist} \cdot (\rho_{ist} + 1)) \geq 0 \]

  • If \(E[\epsilon]=0\), then remain so long as productivity increases:

\[\Delta_{it}( \rho_{ist}) \geq 0\]

Change Operator

Theoretical Framework

Predictions: Imperfect Information

  • Workers will remain working in sports if \(\omega_{ist} \geq \eta_{ist}\)

\[ \Delta_{it} (\rho_{ist} + \epsilon_{ist} \cdot (\rho_{ist} + 1)) \geq 0 \]

  • If \(E[\epsilon] \neq 0\), then remaining depends upon changes in productivity (\(\Delta p \lessgtr -1\))
    • Those with declining productivity are more likely to exit; cannot internalize risk into wages
    • Those with rising productivity are more likely to stay; internalize risk into wages (aided by exit of colleagues with declining productivity)

Empirics

Stacked Difference-in-Differences

  • Stacked DiD: Centering in Event Time
  1. âSliceâ time window: 9 years (4 seasons pre and 5 seasons post treatment event)
  1. Store ID for each treated player so that they never appear in control group
  1. The data are âstackedâ into one dataset with treatment timing that is centered at the same relative event time

Empirics

Two-Way Fixed-Effects Models

OLS; Average TWFE

\[ Y_{sit} = \alpha_{si} + \delta_{st} + \beta T_{sit} + \epsilon_{sit} \]

OLS; Dynamic TWFE

\[ Y_{sit} = \alpha_{si} + \delta_{st} + \sum_{\tau=-4}^{-2} \beta_\tau T_{i\tau} + \sum_{\tau = 0}^{4} \gamma_\tau T_{i\tau} + \epsilon_{sit} \] Poisson; Average TWFE

\[ log(E[Y_{sit}]) = \alpha_{si} + \delta_{st} + \beta T_{sit} + \epsilon_{sit} \]

Empirics

Matching

  • I use the commonly employed Coarsened Exact Matching (CEM) technique to adjust for covariate differences between (pre-treatment) treated and control groups.

  • CEM:

    • âcoarsensâ values of covariates (bins them into groups of broader categories a.k.a âstrataâ) to ensure that both the mean and distribution of each covariate is similar across groups.
    • removes bad control units.
    • assigns weights to account for any remaining differences between groups.

Familiarity Matters

  • The modal career length for hockey is over 30% longer than for football while team sizes are over 100% smaller
    • This means that the modal hockey player will have been teammates with someone who dies of CTE and will have had greater exposure to them prior to their death

Hypothesis III

Bargaining Power & Wage Flexibility Matter

  • The collective bargaining agreement covering hockey players fully guarantees salaries which comes at the expense of:
    • highly restrictive salary caps (limits on the sum of labor costs)
    • escrow payments (withheld salary; dependent upon league revenues)
  • Salary cap per worker in 2024:
    • NFL \(\approx \$6.21M\) per worker
    • NHL \(\approx \$3.82M\) per worker

Results

Back-of-the-Envelope Calculation: Compensation and Indifference

Conclusion

  • I find that workers labor supply is highly elastic with respect to peer health shocks, even in environments where these risks are widely known and highly discussed.
    • Familiarity, recency and wage flexibility help explain this finding.
  • These findings indicate that individuals significantly underestimate the utility loss associated with risky behaviors even in settings where such risks are widely known and discussed.
    • Suggests that public safety policies can provide complementary benefits.

Appendix

Change Operator

  • Unit fixed-effects: \(\Delta X_i = X_{it} - \frac{1}{T} \sum_{\tau = 1}^T x_{i \tau}\)

  • Time fixed-effects: \(\Delta X_i = X_{it} - \frac{1}{I} \sum_{\iota = 1}^I x_{\iota t}\)

  • For notational simplicity, I denote unit and time fixed-effects as \(\Delta_i\) and \(\Delta_t\) respectively.

Overview of Literature

Peer Effects

  • Peer effects are frequently studied in randomized settings, such as classrooms and workplaces, with research showing impacts on:
    • income (Chetty et al. 2011)
    • education (Sacerdote 2001)
    • health behaviors (Kremer and Levy 2008)
    • social attitudes (Carrell, Hoekstra, and West 2019)
  • Workplace peer effects are observed in productivity and behavior through social pressure (Falk and Ichino 2006; Mas and Moretti 2009; Cohen-Zada, Dayag, and Gershoni 2024).

Back

Overview of Literature

Compensating Wage Differentials

  • In non-competitive labor markets, injury risks may not be fully reflected in wages (Fishback and Kantor 1992; Bender and Mridha 2011; Lavetti 2020).
    • This leads to higher quit rates and reduced human capital accumulation (BÃ¶ckerman and Ilmakunnas 2009).
  • Unions increase wages and mitigate compensation costs but were less effective at reducing injury risks (Fishback 1986; Kim and Fishback 1999).

Back

Overview of Literature

Compensating Wage Differentials

  • In sports, wages have been show to be responsive to:
    • employer characteristics and location amenities (Michaelides 2010)
    • injury risk (Dole and Kassis 2010)
    • risk of re-injury (Anderson 2022)
